Yes. I believe the bug rises from some code like:<p><pre><code>    if (newkey->callback != NULL) {
        newkey->callback()
    }
</code></pre>
If newkey structure was not zeroed, then the callback would have had some contents from previous use and the NULL check would have passed and some unintended memory position would be called.

From the diff:<p><pre><code>  -	newkey = xmalloc(sizeof(*newkey));
  +	newkey = xcalloc(1, sizeof(*newkey));
</code></pre>
The only change is that the allocated memory is zeroed, right? (Just  wondering if I&#x27;m missing something.)
